WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:06.320
High up in the Turkish Taurus Mountains, meltwater&nbsp;
streams collect into two major drainage basins,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:11.840
giving birth to the Euphrates and Tigris rivers.&nbsp;
While their closest headwaters lie just a few&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:17.520
hundred meters apart, it won’t be for another&nbsp;
1000 kilometers that these rivers become united.&nbsp;

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:22.160
As the longest and most influential rivers of&nbsp;
western Asia, they are winding their way down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.360
from the Armenian Highlands, rapidly growing&nbsp;
in size. While crossing Syria, the three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:32.320
largest tributaries are joining the course of the&nbsp;
Euphrates and by the time the river enters Iraq,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.320 --> 00:00:37.760
it has reached its maximum size. Leaving the&nbsp;
semi-arid steppe behind and entering the true&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.760 --> 00:00:43.360
desert of Iraq, no more natural tributaries join the&nbsp;
rivers course and man made water management canals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:48.560
start defining the hydrological system.
Roughly 190 kilometers before the delta,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:52.480
the channels of the Euphrates and Tigris&nbsp;
finally merge in the city of Al Qurnah,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:57.200
forming the Shatt Al-Arab, which brings&nbsp;
the united waters to the Persian Gulf.&nbsp;

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:02.640
Throughout this journey, dams, canals, floodwater&nbsp;
catchments and irrigation schemes have made the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:08.160
system one of the most altered on earth.
The state-led Southeast Anatolia Project&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:12.320
turned the Turkish Euphrates into&nbsp;
a chain of hydropower reservoirs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:17.520
culminating in the Atatürk Dam which has been&nbsp;
widely criticised for shifting leverage upstream&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:21.760
and giving Turkey the ability to drastically&nbsp;
curb flows on the Euphrates river.&nbsp;

00:01:21.760 --> 00:01:27.200
Further downstream, human impact shifts from&nbsp;
mega-dams to extensive canal and irrigation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.200 --> 00:01:31.120
projects, linking the mid sections of&nbsp;
the Euphrates and Tigris together and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:35.360
sustaining a large-scale agricultural&nbsp;
zone amidst the arid desert of central&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:40.720
Iraq. The most important agricultural&nbsp;zone 
however, lies between confluence and the delta.&nbsp;

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:44.960
The so-called Mesopotamian marshes have&nbsp;
been populated for thousands of years&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:50.720
and are widely regarded as the birthplace of&nbsp;
civilization. Abundant edible crops but a lack&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:55.440
of precipitation lead to the first irrigation&nbsp;
channels and water management projects in human&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:01.040
history. To manage this, the first writing and&nbsp;
accounting systems were invented by the Sumerians,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:05.520
turning grain, labor, and water rights&nbsp;
into records, which eventually led to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:10.800
bureaucracy and the first civilizations.
What once was an extensive marsh land with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:16.560
seasonal inundated wetland, has been transformed&nbsp;
beyond recognition in the second part of the 20th&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:21.600
century. Dikes and redistribution channels&nbsp;
confined the waters to their normal river&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:25.840
channels, reclaiming the marshlands for&nbsp;
agriculture and oil exploration, leading&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.840 --> 00:02:33.360
to over 90% of the wetland drying up and falling&nbsp;
to human use between the 1970s and 2003. With the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:38.240
fall of Saddam Hussein, who was a major driver&nbsp;
in the eradication of the natural marshland,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:42.400
revitalization in the region has started,&nbsp;
but with ever increasing flow reduction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:48.160
due to irrigation needs and upstream dams,&nbsp;
this ecosystem may never be restored again.&nbsp;

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:53.200
If you are curious about how other rivers&nbsp;
shape civilizations, I have a whole playlist,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:58.160
exploring the most important rivers of our&nbsp;
planet here. See you in the next one, cheers.

